  <datafield tag="520" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">We discuss a modified gravity theory defined by <math altimg="si1.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi>f</mi><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>R</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo>=</mo><msubsup><mrow><mo>∑</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>l</mi></mrow></msubsup><msub><mrow><mi>α</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub><msup><mrow><mi>M</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>−</mo><mi>n</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow></msup><msup><mrow><mi>R</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msup></math> . We consider both finite and infinite number of terms in the series while requiring that the Einstein frame potential of the theory has a flat area around any of its stationary points. We show that the requirement of maximally flat stationary point leads to the existence of the saddle point (local maximum) for even (odd) l . In both cases for <math altimg="si2.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi>l</mi><mo stretchy="false">→</mo><mo>∞</mo></math> one obtains the Starobinsky model with small, exponentially suppressed corrections. Besides the GR minimum the Einstein frame potential has an anti de Sitter vacuum. However we argue that the GR vacuum is absolutely stable and AdS can be reached neither via classical evolution nor via quantum tunnelling. Our results show that a Starobinsky-like model is the only possible realisation of <math altimg="si3.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi>f</mi><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>R</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></math> theory with an extremely flat area in the Einstein frame potential.</subfield>
